<subSubSection id="59F4654C560C6948C88C00BD80EFFD25" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="64" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="115136C7560C6948C88C00BD80EFFD25" blockId="3.[151,1436,1953,2016]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,151,1293]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="64" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560C694FC88C00BD8203F837" bold="true" box="[151,276,1953,1979]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560C694FC9FF00BE8046F837" authority="Ranjan, Singh &amp; Kirti" authorityName="Ranjan, Singh &amp; Kirti" authorityYear="2022" box="[484,849,1953,1979]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dodaki" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560C694FC9FF00BE815BF837" box="[484,588,1953,1979]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">T. dodaki</emphasis>
Ranjan, Singh &amp; Kirti
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560C694FCB4700BD80A1F837" bold="true" box="[860,950,1953,1979]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="38A957AE560C694FCB4700BD80A1F837" box="[860,950,1953,1979]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560C694FCBDC00BD873CF830" box="[967,1067,1953,1980]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1829,1853]" captionTargetBox="[164,1416,193,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-19@2.[151,1436,179,1803]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Imago of Teliphasa spp. 1, male &amp; 2, female, T. nubilosa; 3, male &amp; 4, female, T. hamata; 5, male, holotype &amp; 6, male, paratype, T. dodaki sp. nov.;" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577734/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Figs 5, 6</figureCitation>
) is very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560C694FCD1A00BE8682F837" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1888" box="[1281,1429,1953,1979]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orbiculifer">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560C694FCD1A00BE8682F837" box="[1281,1429,1953,1979]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">T. orbiculifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but is distinct in the forewing lacking a medial zigzag line, and in the pale fulvous hindwing with a fuscous postmedial line and the area beyond it concolorous except for the fuscous apex, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948CC69078B8611FF3D" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1888" box="[1138,1286,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orbiculifer">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CC69078B8611FF3D" box="[1138,1286,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. orbiculifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the forewing exhibits a medial zigzag line, and the hindwing is pale yellowish–cinereous in male, with a slender, curved purplish–brown discal line and a broad marginal band (
<bibRefCitation id="757F4B36560B6948CAF907C380BCFF75" author="Moore, F." box="[738,939,223,249]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" pagination="199 - 299" refId="ref5324" refString="Moore, F. (1888) Descriptions of Indian Lepidoptera Heterocera from the collection of the late Mr. W. S. Atkinson. In: Hewitson, W. C. &amp; Moore, F., Descriptions of new Indian lepidopterous Insects from the collection of the late Mr. W. S. Atkinson 3. Asiatic Society of Bengal Calcutta and Taylor &amp; Francis, London, pp. 199 - 299, pls. 6 - 8." type="book chapter" year="1888">Moore 1888: 201</bibRefCitation>
). Further, 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948CC0407C38790FF75" authority="Ranjan &amp; Singh &amp; Kirti, 2022" authorityName="Ranjan &amp; Singh &amp; Kirti" authorityYear="2022" box="[1055,1159,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dodaki" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CC0407C38790FF75" box="[1055,1159,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. dodaki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CC9407C387FDFF75" bold="true" box="[1167,1258,223,249]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="38A957AE560B6948CC9407C387FDFF75" box="[1167,1258,223,249]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is distinct from another similar species, 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948C9B3061F8133FE91" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1888" box="[424,548,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nubilosa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948C9B3061F8133FE91" box="[424,548,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. nubilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, by the yellowish forewing ground colour, and the hindwing with a prominent postmedial line, with the area beyond it with faint traces of fuscous suffusion, and a prominent fuscous marginal band present, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948C9AF06578127FEE9" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1888" box="[436,560,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nubilosa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948C9AF06578127FEE9" box="[436,560,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. nubilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the forewing ground colour is dark greyish–green and the hindwing is almost uniformly fuscous, except the basal costal area, with the hindwing marginal band diffused with fuscous ground colour (
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560B6948C8CF068F8203FE21" box="[212,276,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1829,1853]" captionTargetBox="[164,1416,193,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-19@2.[151,1436,179,1803]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Imago of Teliphasa spp. 1, male &amp; 2, female, T. nubilosa; 3, male &amp; 4, female, T. hamata; 5, male, holotype &amp; 6, male, paratype, T. dodaki sp. nov.;" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577734" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577734/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). In the male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948CA2F068F818DFE21" authority="Ranjan &amp; Singh &amp; Kirti, 2022" authorityName="Ranjan &amp; Singh &amp; Kirti" authorityYear="2022" box="[564,666,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dodaki" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CA2F068F818DFE21" box="[564,666,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. dodaki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CABA068F81EDFE21" bold="true" box="[673,762,403,429]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="38A957AE560B6948CABA068F81EDFE21" box="[673,762,403,429]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560B6948CB11068F804CFE22" box="[778,859,403,430]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–19" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[269,1315,198,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[247,1340,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 14–19. Male genitalia of Teliphasa spp. 14, T. erythrina; 15, T. nubilosa; 16, T. dodaki sp. nov.; 17, T. similalbifusa; 18, T. hamata; 19, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov.." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577740" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577740/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
), the valva is shorter the vinculum is approximately half the length in comparison to that of 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948CA5506AB81DEFE5D" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1888" box="[590,713,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nubilosa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CA5506AB81DEFE5D" box="[590,713,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. nubilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560B6948CAC106AB803DFE5D" box="[730,810,438,465]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–19" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[269,1315,198,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[247,1340,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 14–19. Male genitalia of Teliphasa spp. 14, T. erythrina; 15, T. nubilosa; 16, T. dodaki sp. nov.; 17, T. similalbifusa; 18, T. hamata; 19, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov.." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577740" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577740/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
), and the aedeagus is cylindrical, while the distal half of the aedeagus is broader in 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948C9A106C78123FE79" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1888" box="[442,564,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nubilosa">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948C9A106C78123FE79" box="[442,564,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. nubilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948CA5906C781E8FE79" authority="Ranjan &amp; Singh &amp; Kirti, 2022" authorityName="Ranjan &amp; Singh &amp; Kirti" authorityYear="2022" box="[578,767,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dodaki" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CA5906C781E8FE79" box="[578,767,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Teliphasa dodaki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CB1E06C7804AFE79" bold="true" box="[773,861,475,501]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="38A957AE560B6948CB1E06C7804AFE79" box="[773,861,475,501]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is further distinct from the other two similar species 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948C88C06E383E2FD94" baseAuthorityName="Butler" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[151,245,511,536]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amica">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948C88C06E383E2FD94" box="[151,245,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. amica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948C93106E382BBFD95" authorityName="Li" authorityYear="2016" box="[298,428,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erythrina">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948C93106E382BBFD95" box="[298,428,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. erythrina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the enlarged labial palpi reaching up and backwards to prothorax (whereas in both other species the labial palpi only reach up to the frons), the yellowish forewing ground colour and the hindwing with traces of postmedial line (whereas forewing ground colour is fuscous in the other two species except for the medial area of forewing and basal area of hindwing in 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948CABB057781E8FD08" baseAuthorityName="Butler" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[672,767,619,644]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amica">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CABB057781E8FD08" box="[672,767,619,644]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. amica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="757F4B36560B6948CB16057780A2FD09" author="Liu, L. &amp; Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H." box="[781,949,619,645]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" pagination="119 - 137" refId="ref5167" refString="Liu, L., Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H. (2016) Taxonomic review of the genus Teliphasa Moore, 1888 from China, with descriptions of four new species (Lepidoptera, Pyralidae, Epipaschiinae). ZooKeys, 554, 119 - 137. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 554.6177" type="journal article" year="2016">
Liu 
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CB270577807BFD09" box="[828,876,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560B6948CBA405778719FD09" box="[959,1038,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1347,1371]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,193,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-29@5.[159,1428,181,1323]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11–13. Female genitalia of Teliphasa spp. 11, T. nubilosa; 12, T. hamata; 13, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577738" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577738/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
) and the forewing with rusty brown scales and an absent postmedial line in the hindwing of 
<taxonomicName id="D6EE4D44560B6948CB130593809BFD25" authorityName="Li" authorityYear="2016" box="[776,908,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Teliphasa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erythrina">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948CB130593809BFD25" box="[776,908,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">T. erythrina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560B6948CB87059380C8FD25" box="[924,991,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1198,1222]" captionTargetBox="[168,1413,193,1164]" captionTargetId="figure-29@3.[151,1435,181,1175]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. Imago of Teliphasa spp. 7, male &amp; 8, female, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov; 9, male, T. erythrina; 10, male, T. similalbifusa." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577736" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577736/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
)).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="59F4654C560B6948C8DC05AE83E8FBD5" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" type="description">
<paragraph id="115136C7560B6948C8DC05AE83C5FC29" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1293]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis id="239AEAD5560B6948C8DC05AE824CFD40" bold="true" box="[199,347,690,716]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Description:</emphasis>
Adult with labial palpi upturned reaching up to prothorax. Antennae in male ciliated (female unknown). Forewing covered with olivaceous fulvous scales. Basal area fuscous. Postmedial line outwardly bent at middle, then obliquely running inward up to hind margin. A dark discal spot with white scales. Chequered fuscous spots from apex to tornus. Colour of ciliae alternating between fuscous and fulvous. Hindwing pale fulvous, faint traces of pale fulvous postmedial line; a fuscous patch at apex; outer margin with fuscous spot. Abdomen covered with alternating transverse bands of fuscous and white scales. Legs covered with fuscous scales accept tip on each joint.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="115136C7560B6948C8DC04B383E8FBD5" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1293]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Male genitalia with uncus short; a sclerotised membrane running parallel to the tegumen and joined at tegumen-vinculum junction; tegumen ribbon-shaped; vinculum U-shaped, saccus reduced; juxta split into two separate arms; transtilla membranous; gnathos arms heavily sclerotised, reaching up, then arching medio-ventrad; valva rounded fan-like, costa straight to slightly concave; aedeagus elongate, slightly bent at middle, vesica with a small cornutus.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
